                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18460817-1738-offence-1 t18460817-name-1372"></join>Thomas Cooper</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460817-name-1373" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1373" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1373" type="surname" value="COOPER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1373" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS COOPER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a baker, and live in Bermondsey-street prisoner was in my service—I received information, and on the 31st of when he came out of the bakehouse into the shop, I told him I wanted him to fetch me 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. worth of milk—he seemed very much alarmed and said, "Now</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184608170227"></xptr>
               <p>Sir, before I serve the coffee-shop"—I said, "Yes now"—he turned round and ran down into the bakehouse with his basket—I followed him and detected him taking one bag of flour out of his basket, and the other I stopped him with before he took it out—I asked him what he had got there—he said a little flour, and he had taken it out of the trough.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALDWIN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was not he in the habit of taking goods out, and taking a book and accounting to you weekly? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I positively swear he did not—the bread was counted out from the shop every day, and it was his duty when he returned from the customers to account for it—it would have been fraud for him to take out a pound of flour, unless I or some person gave it him—if he had an order for flour it would have been bit duty to ask for it—he had conducted himself well—he had been with me about eight months—I have no business to know the bag this flour was in—it was brought on my premises by stealth—I know the flour to be mine—it was impossible for other flour to come on my premises—this flour was kept where he could not have got it out, but by stealth—it was kept in my bakehouse—I found 27lbs. of flour in one bag and 68lbs. in the two bags—I could not have missed it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did it correspond with your flour? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It resembled mine—it was impossible it could be any other than mine—I am nearly blind.</p>
               <p>
